# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**Java MapReduce** is the Java-based Application Programming Interface (API) provided by the **Apache Hadoop** framework that enables developers to write distributed data processing applications using the **MapReduce programming paradigm**. It consists of a set of Java classes and interfaces (found in the packages `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce` and `org.apache.hadoop.mapred`) that allow programs to be automatically parallelized and executed across large clusters of commodity hardware.

In KTU 2024 Scheme terminology, Java MapReduce is the implementation layer where the two functional primitives — the **`map()`** function and the **`reduce()`** function — are coded as Java classes extending framework-provided base classes (specifically `Mapper` and `Reducer`).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Definition to Memorize:**
> *"Java MapReduce is a framework that allows Java developers to write programs capable of processing vast amounts of data (multi-terabyte datasets) in parallel across a Hadoop cluster by inheriting from the `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper` and `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer` base classes and configuring execution via the `Job` class."*

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you are the **librarian of a massive library with 10 million books** and the President asks you: *"How many times does the word 'Democracy' appear across all books?"*

You cannot do this alone. So you hire **1000 assistants** (worker nodes) and apply the **MapReduce strategy**:

1. **MAP PHASE (Sorting onto tables):**  
   Each assistant takes a shelf of books, reads the pages, and for every occurrence of "Democracy" writes a small slip: `( "Democracy", 1 )`. They then place each slip onto a labelled table corresponding to the word. This is the **mapping** — converting raw data into structured `(key, value)` pairs.

2. **SHUFFLE & SORT PHASE (Grouping slips):**  
   A logistics team gathers all slips from every table and groups them by key. All "Democracy" slips from all 1000 assistants land in one bucket.

3. **REDUCE PHASE (Counting):**  
   One accountant per bucket (say, one per unique word) takes their bucket and adds up all the `1`s: `1 + 1 + 1 + ... = 437`. The final answer is written down.

In this analogy:
- **You (the Java programmer)** = write the `Mapper` (assistant) and `Reducer` (accountant) classes.
- **The Hadoop framework** = the logistics team, the table organizers, and the manager.
- **The 1000 assistants** = the worker nodes in the Hadoop cluster.

---

## 1.3 Why Java MapReduce? — Syllabus Highlights

> [!NOTE]
> **Core Reasons Java is the Native Language of MapReduce:**
> 1. **First-class Hadoop API support** — written in Java.
> 2. **Type safety** via Hadoop's `Writable` and `WritableComparable` interfaces.
> 3. **Performance** — JVM-level execution with JNI for native operations.
> 4. **Direct access to Hadoop internals** (partitioners, combiners, counters, distributed cache).
> 5. **Industry standard** for production-grade ETL jobs.

### 1.4 The Three Pillars of a Java MapReduce Program

A complete Java MapReduce program is built from **three mandatory Java classes**:

| Pillar | Base Class | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| **Mapper Class** | `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper<KEYIN, VALUEIN, KEYOUT, VALUEOUT>` | Transforms input records into intermediate `(key, value)` pairs. |
| **Reducer Class** | `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer<KEYIN, VALUEIN, KEYOUT, VALUEOUT>` | Aggregates intermediate pairs sharing the same key. |
| **Driver Class** | A regular Java class with a `main()` method using `Job`, `Configuration`, `FileInputFormat`, `FileOutputFormat` | Configures and submits the MapReduce job to the Hadoop cluster. |

---

## 1.5 Data Types — The Hadoop Writable Ecosystem

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Hadoop **does not use standard Java serialization** (because it's slow and verbose). Instead, it uses a custom, compact, fast serialization framework called **`Writable`**.

| Java Standard Type | Hadoop `Writable` Equivalent | Used As |
|---|---|---|
| `String` | `Text` | Most text data |
| `int` | `IntWritable` | Integer counts |
| `long` | `LongWritable` | File offsets, byte counts |
| `float` | `FloatWritable` | Float metrics |
| `double` | `DoubleWritable` | Double precision metrics |
| `boolean` | `BooleanWritable` | Flags |
| `null` (no value) | `NullWritable` | Key or value placeholders |

For **keys that need to be sorted and partitioned**, Hadoop provides the sub-interface **`WritableComparable<T>`** (which extends both `Writable` and `java.lang.Comparable<T>`). All built-in numeric Writable types implement this.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why `WritableComparable` for keys?**  
> Because in the Shuffle & Sort phase, Hadoop sorts intermediate keys globally. The keys must therefore be both serializable (Writable) and comparable (Comparable) — hence the combined interface.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Mapper Class — Operational Breakdown

The Mapper runs in **three logical stages** (Hadoop invokes them via template method pattern):

| Method | Signature | When Called | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| `setup()` | `protected void setup(Mapper.Context context)` | Once per mapper task, before any `map()` calls | Initialization (e.g., open DB connections, read distributed cache files). |
| `map()` | `protected void map(KEYIN key, VALUEIN value, Mapper.Context context)` | **Once per input record** (i.e., once per line for text input) | The **core transformation logic**. Emits intermediate `(key, value)` pairs via `context.write(k, v)`. |
| `cleanup()` | `protected void cleanup(Mapper.Context context)` | Once per mapper task, after all `map()` calls | Resource release (close connections, flush buffers). |

### The `Context` Object — The Mapper's Communication Channel

The `Context` object passed to `map()` is the **bridge** between the user's logic and the Hadoop framework. Critical methods:

- `context.write(K key, V value)` — Emit an intermediate pair.
- `context.getCounter(Enum, String)` — Increment a custom Hadoop Counter.
- `context.progress()` — Signal liveness to avoid speculative execution kill.
- `context.getConfiguration()` — Access job configuration.

---

## 2.2 The Reducer Class — Operational Breakdown

The Reducer also runs in **three stages**:

| Method | Signature | When Called | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| `setup()` | `protected void setup(Reducer.Context context)` | Once per reducer task, before any `reduce()` calls | Initialization. |
| `reduce()` | `protected void reduce(KEYIN key, Iterable<VALUEIN> values, Reducer.Context context)` | **Once per unique key** | The **aggregation logic**. Iterates over all values for that key, emits output via `context.write()`. |
| `cleanup()` | `protected void cleanup(Reducer.Context context)` | Once per reducer task, after all `reduce()` calls | Final cleanup. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `Iterable<VALUEIN> values` is a **single-pass iterator** backed by the sorted spill file. If you need to iterate twice, you must **buffer the values into a List first** inside the reducer.

---

## 2.3 The Driver Class — The Job Orchestrator

The Driver class is a **plain Java class with `public static void main(String[] args)`**. It performs six critical steps:

1. **Create a `Configuration` object** — reads `core-site.xml`, `mapred-site.xml`, etc.
2. **Create a `Job` object** — `Job.getInstance(conf, "JobName")`.
3. **Set the JAR, Mapper, Reducer classes** — `job.setJarByClass(Driver.class)`, `setMapperClass()`, `setReducerClass()`.
4. **Set output key/value types** — `setOutputKeyClass()`, `setOutputValueClass()`.
5. **Set input/output paths** — `FileInputFormat.addInputPath()`, `FileOutputFormat.setOutputPath()`.
6. **Submit and monitor** — `job.waitForCompletion(true)`.

```java
// Canonical Driver skeleton (Karnataka-style, but Java syntax is universal)
Configuration conf = new Configuration();
Job job = Job.getInstance(conf, "WordCount");
job.setJarByClass(WordCountDriver.class);
job.setMapperClass(WordCountMapper.class);
job.setReducerClass(WordCountReducer.class);
job.setOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
job.setOutputValueClass(IntWritable.class);
FileInputFormat.addInputPath(job, new Path(args[0]));
FileOutputFormat.setOutputPath(job, new Path(args[1]));
System.exit(job.waitForCompletion(true) ? 0 : 1);
```

---

## 2.4 Partitioner, Combiner, and Other Extensions

| Component | Base Class | Role |
|---|---|---|
| **Partitioner** | `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Partitioner<KEY, VALUE>` | Decides which **reducer** receives a given intermediate `(key, value)` pair. Default: `HashPartitioner` → `key.hashCode() mod numReducers`. |
| **Combiner** | A `Reducer` class reused as a local aggregator | Runs **on the mapper node** to perform mini-reductions, reducing network traffic. Must be **commutative and associative**. |
| **Counter** | `enum` extending `Counters.Counter` | Global atomic counters for metrics, debugging. |
| **DistributedCache** | `job.addCacheFile(new URI(...))` | Ship read-only files (e.g., stop-word lists, lookup tables) to all nodes. |

---

## 2.5 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The "formulas" in MapReduce are the **method signatures, type parameters, and configuration property keys** that KTU examiners love to test.

### 2.5.1 Mapper Type Parameters

$$
\text{Mapper}\langle \underbrace{KEYIN}_{\text{input key}}, \underbrace{VALUEIN}_{\text{input value}}, \underbrace{KEYOUT}_{\text{intermediate key}}, \underbrace{VALUEOUT}_{\text{intermediate value}} \rangle
$$

### 2.5.2 Number of Mappers Formula

$$
N_{\text{mappers}} = \sum_{i=1}^{F} \left\lceil \frac{\text{Size of file } i}{\text{Input Split Size (HDFS block size, default 128 MB)}} \right\rceil
$$

where $F$ is the number of input files. **Note:** Split size = `mapreduce.input.fileinputformat.split.maxsize` or `minsize`.

### 2.5.3 HashPartitioner Formula

$$
\text{reducer\_id} \;=\; \left( \text{key.hashCode()} \;\&\; \text{Integer.MAX\_VALUE} \right) \;\bmod\; N_{\text{reducers}}
$$

The `& Integer.MAX_VALUE` clears the sign bit to avoid negative modulo.

### 2.5.4 Combiner Output Reduction

$$
\text{Network Traffic} \;\propto\; \sum_{i=1}^{N_{\text{mappers}}} \vert V_i \vert \;-\; \sum_{i=1}^{N_{\text{mappers}}} \vert C_i \vert
$$

where $\vert V_i \vert$ = intermediate values emitted by mapper $i$, and $\vert C_i \vert$ = values after local combiner reduction. A good combiner **drastically reduces** $\text{Network Traffic}$.

### 2.5.5 Common Configuration Properties (KTU Favourite)

| Property Key | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `mapreduce.job.reduces` | `1` | Number of reduce tasks. |
| `mapreduce.map.output.compress` | `false` | Compress map output (recommended: `true`). |
| `mapreduce.map.cpu.vcores` | `1` | vCPU cores per mapper. |
| `mapreduce.job.map.class` | (none) | Fully qualified Mapper class. |
| `mapreduce.job.reducer.class` | (none) | Fully qualified Reducer class. |
| `mapreduce.input.fileinputformat.split.minsize` | `0` | Minimum split size. |
| `mapreduce.input.fileinputformat.split.maxsize` | `Long.MAX_VALUE` | Maximum split size. |

### 2.5.6 Real-World Utility

- **Log analytics** (e.g., counting unique IPs in server logs at Yahoo, Facebook).
- **ETL pipelines** ingesting data into HDFS/Hive data warehouses.
- **Search index building** (the canonical Google use-case).
- **Distributed sorts, joins, and aggregations** for data lake preprocessing.
- **Machine learning preprocessing** (feature engineering at scale).

---

## 2.6 Data Flow Through MapReduce (Theoretical Path)

$$
\text{Input} \;\xrightarrow{\text{InputFormat}}\; \text{Splits} \;\xrightarrow{\text{RecordReader}}\; (K_1, V_1) \;\xrightarrow{\text{map()}}\; (K_2, V_2)^{*} \;\xrightarrow{\text{Combiner (opt.)}}\; (K_2, V_2') \;\xrightarrow{\text{Partitioner}}\; \text{reducer}_j \;\xrightarrow{\text{Group\&Sort}}\; \text{Iterable}\langle V_2 \rangle \;\xrightarrow{\text{reduce()}}\; (K_3, V_3) \;\xrightarrow{\text{OutputFormat}}\; \text{Output}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The four type pairs $(K_1, V_1)$, $(K_2, V_2)$, $(K_3, V_3)$ may all be **different types** — for example, `(LongWritable, Text)` for input, `(Text, IntWritable)` for intermediate, `(Text, IntWritable)` for output.
