# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 The Canonical WordCount Example — Full Derivation

We will derive (i.e., build up) a complete Java MapReduce program for the **WordCount** problem, the "Hello World" of Hadoop.

### 3.1.1 Problem Statement

> Given a text file (or many text files) stored in HDFS, count the number of occurrences of every distinct word.

**Mathematical Definition:**

$$
\forall w \in W \;:\; \text{count}(w) \;=\; \sum_{(k,v) \in D} \mathbb{1}\{v \text{ contains } w\}
$$

where $W$ is the set of unique words, and $D$ is the dataset of input records.

### 3.1.2 Step-by-Step Mapper Derivation

**Step 1 — Identify type parameters.**

- Input is a text file → `KEYIN = LongWritable` (byte offset), `VALUEIN = Text` (one line of text).
- Output should be `(word, 1)` → `KEYOUT = Text`, `VALUEOUT = IntWritable`.

**Step 2 — Override the `map()` method.**

**Step 3 — Tokenize the input line** using `StringTokenizer` (or `String.split("\\s+")` for regex-based splitting — the former is faster and preferred in KTU exams).

**Step 4 — For each token, emit `(word, 1)`.**

```java
// WordCountMapper.java — full derivation
import java.io.IOException;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.LongWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Mapper;

public class WordCountMapper extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable> {

    // Optimization: declare output objects ONCE and reuse (Hadoop best practice)
    private final static IntWritable one = new IntWritable(1);
    private Text word = new Text();

    @Override
    protected void map(LongWritable key, Text value, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        // Step 3: Tokenize the line
        StringTokenizer itr = new StringTokenizer(value.toString());
        // Step 4: Emit (word, 1) for each token
        while (itr.hasMoreTokens()) {
            word.set(itr.nextToken());
            context.write(word, one);
        }
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why the `static final IntWritable one`?**  
> In KTU exams and Hadoop best-practice guides, this trick is worth mentioning. The `IntWritable` is **immutable** (no setters on the wrapped `int`), but the **`Text` object is mutable** (it has `set()`). By reusing the same `one` reference for all emissions, you avoid allocating millions of `IntWritable` objects, drastically reducing GC pressure.

### 3.1.3 Step-by-Step Reducer Derivation

**Step 1 — Identify type parameters.**

The reducer's input matches the mapper's output: `KEYIN = Text`, `VALUEIN = IntWritable`.  
We keep output types the same: `KEYOUT = Text`, `VALUEOUT = IntWritable`.

**Step 2 — Initialize a running sum** for each unique key.

**Step 3 — Iterate over the values** and accumulate.

**Step 4 — Emit the final `(word, totalCount)` pair.**

```java
// WordCountReducer.java — full derivation
import java.io.IOException;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer;

public class WordCountReducer extends Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable> {

    @Override
    protected void reduce(Text key, Iterable<IntWritable> values, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        int sum = 0;
        // Step 3: Iterate and accumulate
        for (IntWritable val : values) {
            sum += val.get();
        }
        // Step 4: Emit final pair
        context.write(key, new IntWritable(sum));
    }
}
```

### 3.1.4 Step-by-Step Driver Derivation

```java
// WordCountDriver.java — full derivation
import org.apache.hadoop.conf.Configuration;
import org.apache.hadoop.fs.Path;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Job;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.input.FileInputFormat;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.lib.output.FileOutputFormat;

public class WordCountDriver {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        // Step 1: Configuration
        Configuration conf = new Configuration();

        // Step 2: Create Job
        Job job = Job.getInstance(conf, "Word Count");
        job.setJarByClass(WordCountDriver.class);

        // Step 3: Set Mapper, Reducer
        job.setMapperClass(WordCountMapper.class);
        job.setReducerClass(WordCountReducer.class);

        // Step 4: Set output types
        job.setOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
        job.setOutputValueClass(IntWritable.class);

        // Step 5: Set input/output paths
        FileInputFormat.addInputPath(job, new Path(args[0]));
        FileOutputFormat.setOutputPath(job, new Path(args[1]));

        // Step 6: Submit and exit with status
        System.exit(job.waitForCompletion(true) ? 0 : 1);
    }
}
```

### 3.1.5 Compilation and Execution

```bash
# Step A: Compile
hadoop com.sun.tools.javac.Main WordCountMapper.java WordCountReducer.java WordCountDriver.java -d build/

# Step B: Package into JAR
jar -cvf wordcount.jar -C build/ .

# Step C: Submit to cluster
hadoop jar wordcount.jar WordCountDriver /input/path /output/path
```

### 3.1.6 Analytical Matrix: How Many Mappers and Reducers?

Given:
- Input file size = 640 MB
- HDFS block size = 128 MB

$$
N_{\text{mappers}} = \left\lceil \frac{640 \text{ MB}}{128 \text{ MB}} \right\rceil = 5 \text{ mappers}
$$

If we set `mapreduce.job.reduces = 2`, then:
- `HashPartitioner` assigns each key to one of 2 reducers based on `hashCode() mod 2`.

---

## 3.2 Advanced Example — MaxTemperature (Find Max Temp Per Year)

A classic Hadoop tutorial example from Tom White's *Hadoop: The Definitive Guide* style, re-derived for KTU.

### 3.2.1 Mapper

```java
public class MaxTempMapper extends Mapper<LongWritable, Text, Text, IntWritable> {

    private NcdcRecordParser parser = new NcdcRecordParser();

    @Override
    protected void map(LongWritable key, Text value, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        parser.parse(value);
        if (parser.isValidTemperature()) {
            context.write(new Text(parser.getYear()),
                          new IntWritable(parser.getAirTemperature()));
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.2.2 Reducer

```java
public class MaxTempReducer extends Reducer<Text, IntWritable, Text, IntWritable> {

    @Override
    protected void reduce(Text key, Iterable<IntWritable> values, Context context)
            throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        int maxValue = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        for (IntWritable value : values) {
            maxValue = Math.max(maxValue, value.get());
        }
        context.write(key, new IntWritable(maxValue));
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Reducer Associativity Requirement:**  
> This reducer is a valid combiner too — finding the max of a subset and then the max of subsets gives the global max. **Not all reducers are valid combiners.** Example: computing the mean is *not* a valid combiner (you must use a custom combiner that emits `(sum, count)`).

---

## 3.3 The Combiner Optimization — Worked Out

For WordCount, the combiner is just the **same Reducer class reused**:

```java
job.setCombinerClass(WordCountReducer.class);
```

**Numerical impact:** Suppose the dataset has the line `"hadoop hadoop hadoop"` and a mapper without a combiner would emit:

$$
\{(\text{hadoop},1), (\text{hadoop},1), (\text{hadoop},1)\} \rightarrow 3 \text{ records over network}
$$

With a combiner, the mapper locally aggregates first:

$$
\{(\text{hadoop},3)\} \rightarrow 1 \text{ record over network}
$$

The savings compound across millions of mappers.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Combiner Restriction (KTU Exam Favorite):**  
> The combiner's operation must be **commutative** ($a \oplus b = b \oplus a$) **and associative** ($(a \oplus b) \oplus c = a \oplus (b \oplus c)$). Sum, max, min, product are valid. Mean and median are **not**.

---

## 3.4 Type Compatibility and the `setMapOutputKey/ValueClass` Distinction

By default, the **map output types and reduce output types are assumed identical** in the Driver. If they differ, you must explicitly use:

```java
job.setMapOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
job.setMapOutputValueClass(IntWritable.class);
job.setOutputKeyClass(Text.class);
job.setOutputValueClass(DoubleWritable.class);  // Different from map output!
```

This is essential for jobs like computing the **mean temperature per year** where the map emits `(year, IntWritable)` and the reduce emits `(year, DoubleWritable)`.
