### Question 2 (3 Marks)  
**[KTU University Exam – June 2024, PECPT755]**

> Differentiate between a `Combiner` and a `Partitioner` in a Java MapReduce job. State the commutativity/associativity requirement of a combiner.

#### Model Answer (3 Marks):

| Aspect | Combiner | Partitioner |
|---|---|---|
| **When it runs** | On the **mapper node** after the map output buffer is full. | On the **mapper node** before the record leaves the map task. |
| **Purpose** | **Local mini-reduction** to reduce data shipped over the network. | Decides **which reducer** receives a given intermediate `(key, value)` pair. |
| **Implementation** | Reuses a `Reducer` class via `job.setCombinerClass()`. | Implements `org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Partitioner`. Default: `HashPartitioner`. |
| **Output** | Aggregated intermediate pairs. | A **partition number** (0 to N-1). |

**Combiners must be commutative and associative.** That is, the operation $f$ must satisfy $f(a, b) = f(b, a)$ and $f(f(a, b), c) = f(a, f(b, c))$. This is because the order in which partial aggregations are merged is not guaranteed by the framework. Sum, max, min, product satisfy these properties; mean and median do not.

